==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emaciate
<hw>E*ma"ci*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Emaciated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Emaciating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>emaciatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>emaciare</ets> to make lean;
<ets>e</ets> + <ets>maciare</ets> to make lean or meager, fr.
<ets>macies</ets> leanness, akin to <ets>macer</ets> lean. See
<er>Meager</er>.]</ety> <def>To lose flesh gradually and become very
lean; to waste away in flesh.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>emaciated</xex> and
pined away.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emaciate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Emaciate
<hw>E*ma"ci*ate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to waste away in
flesh and become very lean; <as>as, his sickness <ex>emaciated</ex>
him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emaciate</ent>⟦br⟧

